<TITLE> Flintoff fears he may not play again after knee surgery </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Aug 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - England all-rounder Andrew Flintoff fears he may not play again following an operation on his right knee on Monday. Flintoff, 31, retired from Test cricket after a series of injuries to concentrate on one-day internationals after England regained the Ashes at the Oval last Sunday. "There's a possibility I may not play again," Flintoff told the British newspaper News of the World on Sunday. "It's something I'm going to have to be prepared for in case the operation is not as successful as I hope." Flintoff is unable to bear any weight on his right leg for six to eight weeks and his rehabilitation involves strapping his injured limb to a machine for eight hours a day. "I don't want my career to end like this. My Test career ended with a high by England winning the Ashes and I'd like to finish my one-day career by winning the World Cup," he 
